# Peak Teach Review — Project Rules (Production)

## Hard constraints
- Do **not** change or create any file unless the user explicitly lists it in the request.
- Do **not** refactor unrelated code.
- Preserve existing comments and formatting unless asked.
- Prefer small, localized edits over sweeping rewrites.

## Phase 2: UI-first development (Design before logic)
- Design the UI/UX first (layout, copy, states, empty/loading/error) before adding backend or business logic.
- Reuse existing UI primitives; do not invent new patterns per prompt.
- Lock design tokens:
  - Color: use existing semantic tokens (`bg-background`, `text-foreground`, `border-border`, `text-muted-foreground`, etc.). No ad-hoc hex/rgb colors.
  - Spacing: use Tailwind spacing scale; no inline spacing styles.
  - Typography: reuse existing type patterns (hero/section headings/body/meta) — do not introduce arbitrary font sizes.

## Structure rules
- New UI primitives: `src/components/ui`
- Shared UI (composed components): `src/components/shared`
- Feature code: `src/features/<feature-name>`
- Validation schemas: `src/lib/validation`
- Server/business logic: `src/server/services`

If the repo does not yet contain these paths, ask for an explicit file list before creating/migrating folders.

## Security rules
- Never trust client input. Validate on the server.
- Every data access must enforce authorization + ownership checks.
- No secrets in client code. Use server env vars only.
- Handle errors with safe user messages + detailed server logs.

## Output rules (responses)
- Explain what files you changed and why.
- Provide code blocks for each file edited.
- If uncertain, ask for the exact file list rather than guessing.
